# iptables rules for ZeroTier gateway
# Map into container: -v /volume1/docker/zerotier/iptables:/etc/iptables
# File path inside container: /etc/iptables/rules.v4
#
# NOTE: This file is a reference template. install.sh writes the production
# copy to $DATA_DIR/iptables/rules.v4 with actual interface names substituted.
#
# iptables-restore is ATOMIC: a single invalid line aborts the entire restore
# and NOTHING is applied. Every table here must load cleanly.

# Bypass conntrack for ZeroTier UDP — prevents the default 30s conntrack
# timeout expiring between ZeroTier keepalives (~25s), which causes brief
# cutouts under jitter. NOTRACK flows skip the conntrack state machine.
*raw
-A PREROUTING -p udp --dport 9993 -j NOTRACK
-A OUTPUT -p udp --sport 9993 -j NOTRACK
COMMIT

# Mark traffic forwarded FROM the ZeroTier overlay. POSTROUTING (nat) runs
# after the routing decision and CANNOT match -i (input interface) — doing so
# is an iptables error that aborts the whole restore. The mark set here on the
# packet's skb persists into the nat POSTROUTING chain below, letting us scope
# MASQUERADE to only ZeroTier-forwarded traffic.
*mangle
-A FORWARD -i zt+ -j MARK --set-mark 0x2a
COMMIT

# Allow forwarding between ZeroTier overlay and physical NICs.
# Docker macvlan does NOT inject FORWARD ACCEPT rules automatically.
# NOTRACK'd ZeroTier flows have ctstate UNTRACKED so the ctstate rule
# below does not match them — the explicit interface rules do.
*filter
-A FORWARD -i zt+ -o eth0 -j ACCEPT
-A FORWARD -i zt+ -o eth1 -j ACCEPT
-A FORWARD -i eth0 -o zt+ -j ACCEPT
-A FORWARD -i eth1 -o zt+ -j ACCEPT
-A FORWARD -m conntrack --ctstate RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT
COMMIT

# MASQUERADE scoped to ZeroTier-forwarded traffic only, matched via the
# 0x2a mark set in mangle/FORWARD above (POSTROUTING can't match -i).
# The second rule NATs traffic egressing the ZT interface itself.
*nat
-A POSTROUTING -m mark --mark 0x2a -j MASQUERADE
-A POSTROUTING -o zt+ -j MASQUERADE
COMMIT
